1rp.title: Posterior probability
1rp.clickbait: What we believe, after seeing the evidence and doing a Bayesian update.
1rp.text: "Posterior [1rf probability]" or "posterior [1rb odds]" refers our state of belief after seeing a piece of new evidence and doing a [1ly Bayesian update].  Suppose there are two suspects in a murder, Colonel Mustard and Miss Scarlet.  *Before* determining the victim's cause of death, perhaps, you thought Mustard and Scarlet were equally likely to have committed the murder (50% and 50%).  After determining that the victim was poisoned, you now think that Mustard and Scarlet are respectively 25% and 75% likely to have committed the murder.  In this case, your "[prior_probability prior probability]" of Miss Scarlet committing the murder was 50%, and your "posterior probability" after seeing the evidence was 75%.  %%knows-requisite([conditional_probability]): The posterior probability of a hypothesis $H$ after seeing the evidence $e$ is often denoted by the [1rj conditional probability] $\mathbb P(H|e).$ %%
